0
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Downloaded From www.AllSubs.org

1
00:00:48,804 --> 00:00:53,901
11:55. Almost midnight.

2
00:00:53,942 --> 00:00:57,537
Enough time for one more story.

3
00:00:57,579 --> 00:01:02,573
One more story
before 12:00...

4
00:01:02,618 --> 00:01:05,052
just to keep us warm.

5
00:01:06,755 --> 00:01:13,024
In five minutes,
it will be the 21st of April.

6
00:01:13,062 --> 00:01:18,295
One hundred years ago,
on the 21st of April...

7
00:01:18,333 --> 00:01:22,235
out on the waters
around Spivey Point...

8
00:01:22,271 --> 00:01:27,004
a small clipper ship
drew toward land.

9
00:01:27,042 --> 00:01:31,741
Suddenly, out of the night,
the fog rolled in.

10
00:01:31,780 --> 00:01:34,749
For a moment,
they could see nothing...

11
00:01:34,783 --> 00:01:37,251
not a foot ahead of them.

12
00:01:37,286 --> 00:01:40,983
Then they saw a light.

13
00:01:41,023 --> 00:01:46,484
By God, it was a fire
burning on the shore...

14
00:01:46,528 --> 00:01:51,056
strong enough to penetrate
the swirling mist.

15
00:01:51,100 --> 00:01:55,537
They steered a course
toward the light...

16
00:01:55,571 --> 00:01:59,769
but it was a campfire
like this one.

17
00:01:59,808 --> 00:02:04,211
The ship crashed
against the rocks.

18
00:02:04,246 --> 00:02:06,544
The hull sheared in two.

19
00:02:06,582 --> 00:02:09,551
The mast snapped like a twig...

20
00:02:09,585 --> 00:02:14,579
and the wreckage sank
with all the men aboard.

21
00:02:16,091 --> 00:02:18,218
At the bottom of the sea...

22
00:02:18,260 --> 00:02:22,060
lay the ''Elizabeth Dane''
with her crew...

23
00:02:22,097 --> 00:02:25,555
their lungs
filled with salt water...

24
00:02:25,601 --> 00:02:30,231
their eyes open
and staring into the darkness.

25
00:02:30,272 --> 00:02:34,231
And above,
as suddenly as it had come...

26
00:02:34,276 --> 00:02:36,073
the fog lifted...

27
00:02:36,111 --> 00:02:38,909
receded
back across the ocean...

28
00:02:38,947 --> 00:02:41,609
and never came again.

29
00:02:41,650 --> 00:02:44,915
But it is told
by the fishermen...

30
00:02:44,953 --> 00:02:47,922
and their fathers
and grandfathers...

31
00:02:47,956 --> 00:02:52,359
that when the fog returns
to Antonio Bay...

32
00:02:52,394 --> 00:02:56,353
the men
at the bottom of the sea...

33
00:02:56,398 --> 00:02:59,856
out in the water
by Spivey Point...

34
00:02:59,902 --> 00:03:04,771
will rise up
and search for the campfire...

35
00:03:04,807 --> 00:03:11,303
that led them
to their dark and icy death.

36
00:03:13,682 --> 00:03:19,587
Twelve o' clock,
the 21st of April.

37
00:04:14,076 --> 00:04:15,703
It's twelve midnight...

38
00:04:15,744 --> 00:04:18,110
and we just started
into the witching hour.

39
00:04:18,146 --> 00:04:21,513
This is Stevie Wayne,
on top of the world tonight.

40
00:04:21,550 --> 00:04:24,917
And I'll be here
right up until about 1:00.

41
00:04:52,147 --> 00:04:54,581
I'm all through, Father.

42
00:04:54,616 --> 00:04:57,312
Oh, thank you, Bennett.

43
00:04:57,352 --> 00:05:02,085
I won't need you
until four tomorrow, Bennett.

44
00:05:02,124 --> 00:05:03,455
Yes, sir.

45
00:05:04,760 --> 00:05:07,695
Would you like something to
keep you warm on the way home?

46
00:05:07,729 --> 00:05:10,698
No, thank you.
Father, can I get paid?

47
00:05:12,968 --> 00:05:18,770
Why don't you come in at six
instead of four tomorrow?

48
00:05:18,807 --> 00:05:20,968
Yes, sir.

49
00:05:31,219 --> 00:05:33,119
Bennett?

50
00:06:48,330 --> 00:06:50,059
It's 59 degrees outside.

51
00:06:50,098 --> 00:06:52,828
And let me be the first
to wish Antonio Bay...

52
00:06:52,868 --> 00:06:54,335
a happy birthday.

53
00:06:54,369 --> 00:06:57,896
We're one hundred years old
today.

54
00:06:57,939 --> 00:07:00,169
The weatherman's
been trying to spoil it for us.

55
00:07:00,208 --> 00:07:02,301
He says we may be
in for some rain tonight.

56
00:07:02,344 --> 00:07:06,542
But from where I'm sitting,
it looks like clear skies.

57
00:07:06,581 --> 00:07:09,379
I think the weatherman's
been working too hard.

58
00:07:09,418 --> 00:07:11,352
Well, I'll stay here
for another hour...

59
00:07:11,386 --> 00:07:13,684
just to see if he's right.

60
00:07:13,722 --> 00:07:16,247
And I'm inviting you
to stay here with me.

61
00:07:17,392 --> 00:07:21,556
There's a cutter run aground
over here on the east bay, over.

62
00:07:22,798 --> 00:07:27,030
Global 1X5.
It's the ''Lady Belle Pacific.''

63
00:07:27,069 --> 00:07:31,267
Serial number 024KL596. Over.

64
00:07:31,306 --> 00:07:33,706
Global 1X5,
the ''Lady Belle Pacific''...

65
00:07:33,742 --> 00:07:35,767
is seaworthy, no major damage.

66
00:07:35,811 --> 00:07:37,369
Why don't you
send a tow on over here...

67
00:07:37,412 --> 00:07:40,404
about a quarter mile
above the Boatel. Over.

68
00:11:37,519 --> 00:11:42,115
This is KAB,
Antonio Bay, California.

69
00:11:43,458 --> 00:11:46,484
Six minutes after midnight.

70
00:11:46,528 --> 00:11:47,756
Haven't heard
from the weatherman yet...

71
00:11:47,796 --> 00:11:50,264
so I can't say for sure
about that rain...

72
00:11:50,298 --> 00:11:54,394
but there's a full moon
and no clouds in the sky.

73
00:11:55,904 --> 00:11:57,394
I'm Stevie Wayne.

74
00:11:57,439 --> 00:11:59,873
And if you don't have anything
to do right now...

75
00:11:59,908 --> 00:12:03,901
I'll be here playing music
all through the witching hour.

76
00:12:07,782 --> 00:12:09,875
Even if you do
have something to do...

77
00:12:09,918 --> 00:12:12,045
keep me turned on for a while...

78
00:12:12,087 --> 00:12:14,885
and I'll try my best
to do the same for you.

79
00:12:14,923 --> 00:12:16,117
OK!

80
00:12:37,712 --> 00:12:40,237
- How far you going?
- Other side of town.

81
00:12:40,281 --> 00:12:41,612
That's close enough.

82
00:12:43,451 --> 00:12:46,284
- Make it?
- Yeah. Thank you.

83
00:12:56,731 --> 00:12:58,460
Sip?

84
00:12:58,500 --> 00:12:59,990
Thanks.

85
00:13:06,574 --> 00:13:09,634
Listen,
I never hitchhiked before.

86
00:13:09,677 --> 00:13:11,770
I just really want
to be careful.

87
00:13:11,813 --> 00:13:13,713
- Can I ask you something?
- Sure.

88
00:13:13,748 --> 00:13:16,239
Are you weird?

89
00:13:16,284 --> 00:13:18,445
Yes, I am.

90
00:13:18,486 --> 00:13:20,477
Yes, I am weird.

91
00:13:20,522 --> 00:13:23,047
You are weird.
Thank God you're weird.

92
00:13:23,091 --> 00:13:25,924
The last one was so normal,
it was disgusting.

93
00:13:25,960 --> 00:13:27,757
He picked me up
in Santa Barbara.

94
00:13:27,796 --> 00:13:29,957
By the time we got to Carmel
he wanted to marry me.

95
00:13:29,998 --> 00:13:32,660
Oh, yeah. I thought
you never hitchhiked before.

96
00:13:36,805 --> 00:13:38,796
Not before last week.

97
00:13:38,840 --> 00:13:41,707
You're my...

98
00:13:41,743 --> 00:13:43,301
thirteenth ride.

99
00:13:43,344 --> 00:13:46,074
Oh, great. Weird and unlucky.

100
00:13:46,114 --> 00:13:48,742
We'll see.

101
00:13:51,820 --> 00:13:53,014
Look out!

102
00:13:59,994 --> 00:14:01,256
- Are you all right?
- I'm fine.

103
00:14:01,296 --> 00:14:03,526
- You're sure?
- I think so.

104
00:14:03,565 --> 00:14:05,123
What the hell was...

105
00:14:11,606 --> 00:14:13,801
It's exactly twelve minutes
after midnight...

106
00:14:13,842 --> 00:14:15,707
and this is Stevie Wayne.

107
00:14:15,743 --> 00:14:17,574
Let's get out of here.

108
00:14:19,814 --> 00:14:22,647
I'm high tonight in the KAB
lighthouse on Spivey Point.

109
00:14:22,684 --> 00:14:25,209
And in case you've forgotten,
it's April 21st...

110
00:14:25,253 --> 00:14:27,483
and a happy birthday
for Antonio Bay.

111
00:14:27,522 --> 00:14:30,389
Now, there's a celebration
planned for tonight.

112
00:14:30,425 --> 00:14:34,225
So if you're so excited
about it you can't sleep...

113
00:14:34,262 --> 00:14:36,856
well, stay up with me...

114
00:14:36,898 --> 00:14:42,200
and I'll figure out some way
to keep you occupied.

115
00:14:42,237 --> 00:14:43,397
Or not.

116
00:14:49,010 --> 00:14:50,910
- KAB.
- Hi, sweetheart.

117
00:14:50,945 --> 00:14:53,106
Hi, Dan. What have you got?

118
00:14:53,147 --> 00:14:55,012
Well, I'm just calling
to see if you're lonely...

119
00:14:55,049 --> 00:14:56,277
if there's anything
I can do about it.

120
00:14:56,317 --> 00:14:58,046
Never lonely, Dan.

121
00:14:58,086 --> 00:14:59,348
I thought
you were off work at 8:00.

122
00:14:59,387 --> 00:15:01,787
I changed shifts to make it
to the big party tonight.

123
00:15:01,823 --> 00:15:02,949
Will you be there?

124
00:15:02,991 --> 00:15:06,449
Until I can talk someone else...

125
00:15:06,494 --> 00:15:09,725
into giving up city life
for Antonio Bay, I'm it.

126
00:15:09,764 --> 00:15:12,733
- And ''it'' means day and night.
- Too much work.

127
00:15:12,767 --> 00:15:14,735
That's what I get
for owning a station.

128
00:15:14,769 --> 00:15:15,861
And if you don't tell me
why you called...

129
00:15:15,904 --> 00:15:18,202
in about fifteen seconds,
I'll have to hang up on you.

130
00:15:18,239 --> 00:15:20,707
- Want something to talk about?
- Anything.

131
00:15:20,742 --> 00:15:23,142
I've got a position
on a trawler about...

132
00:15:23,177 --> 00:15:26,840
fifteen miles out
called the ''Sea Grass.''

133
00:15:26,881 --> 00:15:28,439
And I've got
something on my scope...

134
00:15:28,483 --> 00:15:30,383
appears to be a fog bank.

135
00:15:30,418 --> 00:15:33,751
It's about 25 miles out,
moving in their direction.

136
00:15:33,788 --> 00:15:37,519
Thanks, Dan.
That's worth about ten seconds.

137
00:15:37,559 --> 00:15:39,584
I'm on the air. Bye.

138
00:15:44,399 --> 00:15:45,923
Ahoy, maties.

139
00:15:45,967 --> 00:15:48,834
This is KAB, Antonio Bay.

140
00:15:48,870 --> 00:15:52,738
Stevie Wayne here
beaming a signal across the sea.

141
00:15:52,774 --> 00:15:56,005
To the men of the ''Sea Grass,''
fifteen miles out tonight...

142
00:15:56,044 --> 00:15:57,409
a warm hello...

143
00:15:57,445 --> 00:16:00,175
and keep a watch out
for that fog bank...

144
00:16:00,214 --> 00:16:02,011
heading in from the east.

145
00:16:02,050 --> 00:16:03,517
Now, in the meantime...

146
00:16:03,551 --> 00:16:06,179
relax with me
while I play this song...

147
00:16:06,220 --> 00:16:09,849
from the Coupe DeVilles,
dedicated just to you.

148
00:16:09,891 --> 00:16:12,587
Boy, would I like to meet her.

149
00:16:12,627 --> 00:16:13,855
I saw her
at a grocery store one day.

150
00:16:13,895 --> 00:16:15,863
- And?
- You would like to meet her.

151
00:16:15,897 --> 00:16:18,866
She's crazy.
There's no fog bank out there.

152
00:16:18,900 --> 00:16:20,367
What do you know about her?

153
00:16:20,401 --> 00:16:22,733
- She owns that lighthouse.
- I know that.

154
00:16:22,770 --> 00:16:24,533
Her son plays Little League
with my kid brother.

155
00:16:24,572 --> 00:16:25,869
She's a mother?

156
00:16:25,907 --> 00:16:27,534
I thought
you were happily married.

157
00:16:27,575 --> 00:16:29,202
Not that happy.

158
00:16:29,243 --> 00:16:32,041
No fog bank out there.

159
00:16:39,621 --> 00:16:41,589
There's a fog bank out there.

160
00:16:43,424 --> 00:16:46,450
All right. I'm drunk enough.

161
00:16:46,494 --> 00:16:48,428
Let's go back.

162
00:16:48,463 --> 00:16:50,294
All right, all right.

163
00:16:54,469 --> 00:16:56,960
Al, come here.

164
00:16:57,005 --> 00:16:59,303
- Just give him a hand.
- Come here.

165
00:17:11,552 --> 00:17:13,645
What was that?

166
00:17:41,349 --> 00:17:43,408
Come here.

167
00:17:45,920 --> 00:17:47,911
What was that?

168
00:17:56,531 --> 00:17:58,192
It's the generator.

169
00:17:59,534 --> 00:18:01,627
Wha... wha...

170
00:18:05,740 --> 00:18:07,002
Al.

171
00:18:23,391 --> 00:18:24,949
It's gone.

172
00:18:24,992 --> 00:18:26,857
There was just a ship out there.

173
00:18:26,894 --> 00:18:28,521
Al, listen.

174
00:18:28,563 --> 00:18:30,690
Nothing.

175
00:18:30,732 --> 00:18:32,893
- Listen.
- Who's there?

176
00:18:44,078 --> 00:18:46,137
Who is that?

177
00:19:34,996 --> 00:19:36,725
Al, it's right beside us.

178
00:19:39,667 --> 00:19:43,398
It's big, Al. It's a ship.

179
00:19:43,437 --> 00:19:45,200
It's a big ship!

180
00:19:48,910 --> 00:19:50,707
What happened?
Did you get wet?

181
00:20:09,931 --> 00:20:12,729
It's 12:43...

182
00:20:12,767 --> 00:20:15,133
and I've got
four in a row for you...

183
00:20:15,169 --> 00:20:17,433
right here on KAB.

184
00:20:54,041 --> 00:20:56,407
Nothing but water, Stevie.

185
00:20:59,280 --> 00:21:01,407
But it sure beats Chicago.

186
00:21:06,921 --> 00:21:08,218
KAB.

187
00:21:08,256 --> 00:21:09,951
I like what you said...

188
00:21:09,991 --> 00:21:12,289
but for your information,
you lied.

189
00:21:12,326 --> 00:21:14,692
The fog bank
has moved due west...

190
00:21:14,729 --> 00:21:18,358
and probably
missed the ship entirely.

191
00:21:18,399 --> 00:21:20,230
Well, my gauges must be wrong.

192
00:21:20,268 --> 00:21:21,963
I've got a wind blowing
due east.

193
00:21:22,003 --> 00:21:24,563
What kind of a fog
blows against the wind?

194
00:21:24,605 --> 00:21:27,073
- You got me.
- I'm not so sure I want you.

195
00:21:27,108 --> 00:21:28,905
You're just
a voice on the phone.

196
00:21:28,943 --> 00:21:32,242
You're a voice on the radio.
We'd make a perfect couple.

197
00:21:34,248 --> 00:21:37,274
You let me take you to dinner
tonight, I'll prove it to you.

198
00:21:37,318 --> 00:21:39,218
Sorry, Dan.

199
00:21:39,253 --> 00:21:42,484
My idea of perfection
is a voice on the phone.

200
00:21:42,523 --> 00:21:45,219
OK, mystery lady.

201
00:21:45,259 --> 00:21:47,659
- Good night.
- Good night.

202
00:22:08,582 --> 00:22:09,742
Not bad.

203
00:22:11,519 --> 00:22:14,044
I started a week ago
in San Diego...

204
00:22:14,088 --> 00:22:17,489
right up the coast,
five drawings a day.

205
00:22:17,525 --> 00:22:19,322
It'll probably take me a month
to get to Vancouver...

206
00:22:19,360 --> 00:22:20,918
and if I can sell them
for five bucks apiece...

207
00:22:20,962 --> 00:22:23,260
- I'll be rich.
- Yeah.

208
00:22:26,133 --> 00:22:28,067
- Can I ask you something?
- Sure.

209
00:22:28,102 --> 00:22:30,127
What's your name?

210
00:22:30,171 --> 00:22:32,833
- Elizabeth.
- Nick.

211
00:22:32,873 --> 00:22:35,603
- Hello, Nick.
- Hi.

212
00:22:37,378 --> 00:22:39,471
Is that where you're from,
San Diego?

213
00:22:39,513 --> 00:22:41,913
Wait a minute. You said,
''Can I ask something?''

214
00:22:41,949 --> 00:22:44,144
Well, something,
to me, means one thing.

215
00:22:44,185 --> 00:22:46,847
- San Diego is two things.
- OK.

216
00:22:48,622 --> 00:22:53,582
Pasadena, and a lot of money.

217
00:22:53,627 --> 00:22:56,061
Never a chance to do
anything I want to do.

218
00:23:00,735 --> 00:23:02,930
What do you want to do?

219
00:23:02,970 --> 00:23:06,064
I don't know.

220
00:23:06,107 --> 00:23:09,304
That's OK. Me, neither.

221
00:23:09,343 --> 00:23:12,073
I think I got to have this one.
Can I buy it?

222
00:23:13,848 --> 00:23:15,406
The drawing's free.

223
00:24:12,640 --> 00:24:14,938
It's 1:00, straight up...

224
00:24:14,975 --> 00:24:18,570
the end of the witching hour,
and time for me to sign off.

225
00:24:24,885 --> 00:24:27,547
So until tomorrow night,
at 6 P.M...

226
00:24:27,588 --> 00:24:29,715
when KAB
comes back on the air...

227
00:24:29,757 --> 00:24:32,521
this is Stevie Wayne,
your night light...

228
00:24:32,560 --> 00:24:35,461
hoping you have
a nice rest of the night.

229
00:26:33,747 --> 00:26:35,476
Hey, Mom!

230
00:26:40,721 --> 00:26:43,747
Mom, come on. Get up.
Look what I found.

231
00:26:43,791 --> 00:26:48,421
Andy...I love you...

232
00:26:48,462 --> 00:26:50,896
but sometimes
you're a real pain.

233
00:26:50,931 --> 00:26:52,558
Sure, Mom, but look it.

234
00:26:52,600 --> 00:26:53,931
First, it was a gold coin.

235
00:26:53,968 --> 00:26:56,732
Then it turned into
this neat piece of wood.

236
00:26:56,770 --> 00:26:58,328
This is one of those times.

237
00:26:58,372 --> 00:27:00,067
Look at it, Mom.

238
00:27:04,278 --> 00:27:06,246
Good morning, Andrew.

239
00:27:06,280 --> 00:27:08,373
Did you have a nice time
last night?

240
00:27:08,415 --> 00:27:11,407
Yeah. Old Mr. Machen
told us ghost stories.

241
00:27:11,452 --> 00:27:14,182
Did you thank Mrs. Kobritz
for bringing you home?

242
00:27:14,221 --> 00:27:17,520
Yes, ma'am. Mom, can I have
a stomach pounder and a Coke?

243
00:27:17,558 --> 00:27:20,959
- After lunch.
- OK.

244
00:27:20,995 --> 00:27:22,690
I'm gonna go look
for another one.

245
00:27:22,730 --> 00:27:25,221
Maybe this time
I can get the gold coin.

246
00:27:50,024 --> 00:27:51,787
Where the hell is he?

247
00:27:51,825 --> 00:27:53,952
Rolled out of here
at 4:15 yesterday.

248
00:27:53,994 --> 00:27:56,360
- That's the last I saw of him.
- Al said 7:30, right here.

249
00:27:56,397 --> 00:27:58,490
You know Al.
If I were you...

250
00:27:58,532 --> 00:28:00,022
Did you call
the Coast Guard, Hank?

251
00:28:00,067 --> 00:28:02,092
Nick, they probably
got drunk last night.

252
00:28:02,136 --> 00:28:05,003
- No, he wouldn't do that.
- He'd do anything.

253
00:28:05,039 --> 00:28:07,303
Al and I got drunk so many times
I can't count them all...

254
00:28:07,341 --> 00:28:10,640
but we never got so shitfaced
we couldn't make it back in.

255
00:28:10,678 --> 00:28:12,669
He's too good a sailor
to stay out there all night...

256
00:28:12,713 --> 00:28:14,010
and not let somebody know.

257
00:28:14,048 --> 00:28:16,881
- You sound like his wife.
- Just his friend.

258
00:28:16,917 --> 00:28:18,714
- You worry too much, Nick.
- Yeah.

259
00:28:21,455 --> 00:28:23,184
Where are we going?

260
00:28:23,223 --> 00:28:26,192
I'm going to talk Ashcroft
into taking out his boat...

261
00:28:26,226 --> 00:28:27,784
and looking for the ''Sea Grass.''

262
00:28:27,828 --> 00:28:29,295
Who's Ashcroft?

263
00:28:29,330 --> 00:28:31,298
Someone who owes me a favor.

264
00:28:31,332 --> 00:28:33,300
Can I come along?

265
00:28:33,334 --> 00:28:35,802
I thought you had to move on
to Vancouver?

266
00:28:35,836 --> 00:28:37,064
Eventually.

267
00:28:44,244 --> 00:28:46,508
The sheriff
will drive his own car.

268
00:28:46,547 --> 00:28:49,345
The mayor and his wife
are to be picked up at 6:45...

269
00:28:49,383 --> 00:28:51,374
and brought to the mayor's box.

270
00:28:51,418 --> 00:28:53,909
Then we will have speeches
by the mayor...

271
00:28:53,954 --> 00:28:55,819
the sheriff, and me.

272
00:28:55,856 --> 00:28:58,154
- Do you have my notes?
- Yes, ma'am.

273
00:28:58,192 --> 00:28:59,989
Then we will pass out
the candles...

274
00:29:00,027 --> 00:29:01,790
and begin the procession.

275
00:29:01,829 --> 00:29:04,730
Then I will go home
and pass out.

276
00:29:04,765 --> 00:29:06,960
I'm almost afraid to look.

277
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:08,262
Well...

278
00:29:11,171 --> 00:29:13,139
Not bad. Not bad at all.

279
00:29:13,173 --> 00:29:15,004
A work of art.

280
00:29:15,042 --> 00:29:18,170
Sandy, just be civil to me
for another five hours.

281
00:29:18,212 --> 00:29:19,804
That's all I ask.

282
00:29:19,847 --> 00:29:21,314
Let's see now.

283
00:29:21,348 --> 00:29:23,145
The candles.
Did you order the candles?

284
00:29:23,183 --> 00:29:24,912
What a thought... a candlelight
procession with no candles.

285
00:29:24,952 --> 00:29:27,216
All taken care of.

286
00:29:27,254 --> 00:29:29,518
And the promotional material...
did you get that to Stevie?

287
00:29:29,556 --> 00:29:31,990
Signed, sealed, and delivered.

288
00:29:32,025 --> 00:29:34,789
Sandy, you can be a very
annoying person at times...

289
00:29:34,828 --> 00:29:36,193
but you do keep me together.

290
00:29:36,230 --> 00:29:38,221
Thank you, Mrs. Williams.

291
00:30:07,261 --> 00:30:11,357
...Spivey Point.
As of 1:57 today...

292
00:30:11,398 --> 00:30:13,298
the ''Sea Grass''
had not responded...

293
00:30:13,333 --> 00:30:15,233
to radio communication.

294
00:30:15,269 --> 00:30:17,294
The Coast Guard
has begun a sweep...

295
00:30:17,337 --> 00:30:19,032
south from Watley...

296
00:30:19,072 --> 00:30:20,699
around Arcom Reef...

297
00:30:20,741 --> 00:30:22,902
and should be
in the area of Spivey Point...

298
00:30:22,943 --> 00:30:25,411
in approximately one hour.

299
00:30:25,446 --> 00:30:28,745
Repeating this bulletin
from the Coast Guard...

300
00:30:28,782 --> 00:30:30,750
be on the look out
for the ''Sea Grass''...

301
00:30:30,784 --> 00:30:32,581
a thirty-foot trawler...

302
00:30:32,619 --> 00:30:37,056
last seen approximately 15 miles
east of Spivey Point.

303
00:30:37,090 --> 00:30:39,081
If you sight this vessel...

304
00:30:39,126 --> 00:30:41,822
please notify
the Coast Guard immediately.

305
00:30:53,006 --> 00:30:56,942
Nick, can I ask you a question?

306
00:30:56,977 --> 00:30:58,376
Is it always like this?

307
00:30:58,412 --> 00:31:01,381
It's always different.

308
00:31:01,415 --> 00:31:03,440
You're worried, aren't you?

309
00:31:03,484 --> 00:31:06,851
Yeah. She can get real mean.

310
00:31:06,887 --> 00:31:08,252
There.

311
00:31:19,533 --> 00:31:22,468
If I can just get through
the speeches without yawning.

312
00:31:22,503 --> 00:31:24,767
- I couldn't sleep last night.
- Too excited?

313
00:31:24,805 --> 00:31:27,296
No. Al went out on his boat
last night and didn't come home.

314
00:31:27,341 --> 00:31:29,901
- He still isn't back.
- Mrs. Williams!

315
00:31:29,943 --> 00:31:31,376
I called the Coast Guard,
and they said...

316
00:31:31,411 --> 00:31:33,538
''Oh, he might have had
engine trouble.''

317
00:31:33,580 --> 00:31:35,741
They said not to worry.

318
00:31:35,782 --> 00:31:37,409
He was complaining
about his boat last week.

319
00:31:37,451 --> 00:31:38,918
Maybe you ought to go home.

320
00:31:38,952 --> 00:31:41,443
That's the last place
I want to go.

321
00:31:41,488 --> 00:31:43,422
My dog started to bark
at 12:00 last night...

322
00:31:43,457 --> 00:31:45,425
and didn't stop
until 6:00 this morning.

323
00:31:45,459 --> 00:31:46,721
What happened?

324
00:31:46,760 --> 00:31:48,887
He was pointed toward the ocean
and growling.

325
00:31:48,929 --> 00:31:50,089
What does that tell you?

326
00:31:50,130 --> 00:31:52,530
My dog goes crazy and
decides to bark at the water.

327
00:31:52,566 --> 00:31:54,534
I heard the church bells
at midnight...

328
00:31:54,568 --> 00:31:56,365
as I started
to drift off to sleep...

329
00:31:56,403 --> 00:31:59,099
and my car alarm went off
for absolutely no reason.

330
00:31:59,139 --> 00:32:01,699
- Really?
- Woke up the whole block.

331
00:32:01,742 --> 00:32:04,438
This town sits around for
100 years and nothing happens...

332
00:32:04,478 --> 00:32:06,810
and then one night,
the whole place falls apart.

333
00:32:09,383 --> 00:32:12,113
Take this line, too.

334
00:32:12,152 --> 00:32:15,747
Al! Tommy! Dick!

335
00:32:20,427 --> 00:32:22,952
Cabin and steering house
are empty.

336
00:32:22,996 --> 00:32:25,260
Maybe somebody picked them up.

337
00:32:26,934 --> 00:32:28,731
There's water in the generator.

338
00:32:28,769 --> 00:32:30,930
But the deck is dry as a bone.

339
00:32:57,197 --> 00:32:59,324
There you have it.
My next project...

340
00:32:59,366 --> 00:33:02,199
restoration of
the Morgantown Road Cemetery.

341
00:33:02,235 --> 00:33:04,465
It's historical.
Our ancestors are buried here.

342
00:33:04,504 --> 00:33:07,200
- It'll cost a lot.
- Come on. So?

343
00:33:07,240 --> 00:33:09,037
This town should be proud
of its past.

344
00:33:09,076 --> 00:33:10,668
But trying to get
anyone involved...

345
00:33:10,711 --> 00:33:13,145
in community affairs
is like pulling teeth.

346
00:33:13,180 --> 00:33:14,374
Better get
the estimates ready...

347
00:33:14,414 --> 00:33:15,881
for the council meeting
next month.

348
00:33:15,916 --> 00:33:17,042
Yes, ma'am.

349
00:33:17,084 --> 00:33:18,551
Sandy, you're
the only person I know...

350
00:33:18,585 --> 00:33:20,883
who can make ''Yes, ma'am''
sound like ''Screw you.''

351
00:33:20,921 --> 00:33:22,183
Yes, ma'am.

352
00:33:22,222 --> 00:33:23,348
Now, if we'll just say
a little prayer...

353
00:33:23,390 --> 00:33:25,415
asking that
he not be in his cups.

354
00:33:31,865 --> 00:33:33,594
Not a good sign.

355
00:33:36,236 --> 00:33:38,830
Father Malone?

356
00:33:46,813 --> 00:33:49,111
Another bad sign.

357
00:33:49,149 --> 00:33:51,879
You try the study,
and I'll look up front.

358
00:34:15,976 --> 00:34:19,707
- Jesus!
- I'm sorry, Mrs. Williams.

359
00:34:19,746 --> 00:34:22,442
- Mrs. Williams...
- Are you all right?

360
00:34:22,482 --> 00:34:24,575
I have something to show you.

361
00:34:30,123 --> 00:34:32,591
''December 9.

362
00:34:32,626 --> 00:34:36,528
''Met with Blake this evening
for the first time.

363
00:34:36,563 --> 00:34:38,190
''He stood in the shadows...

364
00:34:38,231 --> 00:34:42,031
''to prevent me from getting
a clear look at his face.

365
00:34:42,069 --> 00:34:45,664
''What a vile disease this is.

366
00:34:45,706 --> 00:34:49,665
''He is a rich man
with a cursed condition...

367
00:34:49,710 --> 00:34:51,234
''but this does not
prevent him...

368
00:34:51,278 --> 00:34:53,337
''from trying to better
his situation...

369
00:34:53,380 --> 00:34:55,712
''and that of his comrades
at the colony.''

370
00:35:16,436 --> 00:35:18,961
Every single gauge is broken.

371
00:35:21,341 --> 00:35:23,866
- All the glass is shattered.
- Remind you of something?

372
00:35:23,910 --> 00:35:25,901
- Last night.
- Your truck.

373
00:35:34,054 --> 00:35:36,079
Thermometer's broken.

374
00:35:38,024 --> 00:35:40,584
The mercury's stuck
at twenty degrees.

375
00:35:42,062 --> 00:35:47,864
No water got in here,
but something awful cold did.

376
00:35:47,901 --> 00:35:52,031
''December 11.
Blake's proposition is simple.

377
00:35:52,072 --> 00:35:54,506
''He wants to move off
Tanzier Island...

378
00:35:54,541 --> 00:35:59,205
''and relocate the entire colony
just north of here.

379
00:35:59,246 --> 00:36:01,237
''He has purchased
a clipper ship...

380
00:36:01,281 --> 00:36:06,776
''called the 'Elizabeth Dane.'
with part of his fortune...

381
00:36:06,820 --> 00:36:10,620
''and asks only for permission
to settle here.

382
00:36:10,657 --> 00:36:13,854
''I must balance my feelings
of mercy and compassion...

383
00:36:13,894 --> 00:36:15,953
''toward this poor man...

384
00:36:15,996 --> 00:36:18,521
''with my revulsion
at the thought...

385
00:36:18,565 --> 00:36:22,001
''of a leper colony
only a mile distant.''

386
00:36:40,020 --> 00:36:42,215
It's rusted to the wall.

387
00:36:45,692 --> 00:36:47,125
It was on.

388
00:36:55,035 --> 00:36:57,003
They drank a lot of beer
last night.

389
00:36:57,037 --> 00:36:58,664
Every night.

390
00:36:58,705 --> 00:37:01,003
What's it like?

391
00:37:01,041 --> 00:37:04,010
It's always the same.
Room starts spinning...

392
00:37:04,044 --> 00:37:05,238
I mean fishing.

393
00:37:08,648 --> 00:37:09,842
You fish.

394
00:37:09,883 --> 00:37:11,510
The only thing I know
about fishing...

395
00:37:11,551 --> 00:37:12,882
is you use a lot of worms.

396
00:37:14,988 --> 00:37:16,353
Salt water.

397
00:37:18,658 --> 00:37:21,183
She was clean two nights ago.
I checked her out myself.

398
00:37:21,228 --> 00:37:24,561
Now it's as if she's been
turned over in the water.

399
00:37:26,733 --> 00:37:30,829
''April 20.
The six of us met tonight.

400
00:37:30,871 --> 00:37:32,839
''From midnight until 1:00...

401
00:37:32,873 --> 00:37:36,331
''we planned the death
of Blake and his comrades.

402
00:37:36,376 --> 00:37:39,038
''I tell myself
that Blake's gold...

403
00:37:39,079 --> 00:37:41,047
''will allow
the church to be built...

404
00:37:41,081 --> 00:37:43,777
''and our small settlement
to become a township...

405
00:37:43,817 --> 00:37:47,048
''but it does not soothe
the horror that I feel...

406
00:37:47,087 --> 00:37:50,750
''being an accomplice to murder.''

407
00:37:55,462 --> 00:37:57,259
Now what?

408
00:37:57,297 --> 00:37:59,356
Wait for the Coast Guard.

409
00:38:04,204 --> 00:38:06,195
I'm sorry.

410
00:38:06,239 --> 00:38:07,501
What for?

411
00:38:07,540 --> 00:38:10,532
Ever since you picked me up,
things have been going wrong.

412
00:38:10,577 --> 00:38:12,636
The clock broke, the windows
have been breaking...

413
00:38:12,679 --> 00:38:14,237
the weirdo at the door
last night.

414
00:38:14,281 --> 00:38:17,512
- That isn't you.
- I'm not so sure.

415
00:38:17,550 --> 00:38:20,348
Things seem to happen to me.

416
00:38:20,387 --> 00:38:21,718
I'm bad luck.

417
00:38:23,290 --> 00:38:27,920
I don't believe in luck,
good or bad.

418
00:38:27,961 --> 00:38:30,225
I don't believe
in anything much...

419
00:38:32,699 --> 00:38:35,224
Something did happen once.

420
00:38:37,570 --> 00:38:40,038
My father was a fisherman.

421
00:38:40,073 --> 00:38:44,533
He ran a trawler
out of Whitely Reef.

422
00:38:44,577 --> 00:38:48,911
One night, late,
he was coming back in.

423
00:38:48,949 --> 00:38:52,976
He was out beyond the reef,
out near Spivey Point.

424
00:38:53,019 --> 00:38:55,715
He looked to windward...

425
00:38:55,755 --> 00:38:59,247
and saw a brig
under shortsail...

426
00:38:59,292 --> 00:39:01,522
heading right for him.

427
00:39:04,030 --> 00:39:08,023
And he radioed.
There was no reply.

428
00:39:08,068 --> 00:39:12,664
Nothing moved on the deck,
but she held her course.

429
00:39:13,873 --> 00:39:17,036
My dad and two of his hands
boarded the brig...

430
00:39:17,077 --> 00:39:19,739
the ''Resa Jane.''

431
00:39:19,779 --> 00:39:23,180
No one was on board.

432
00:39:23,216 --> 00:39:25,184
There was food on the table...

433
00:39:25,218 --> 00:39:27,516
and a hot, steaming
cup of coffee.

434
00:39:27,554 --> 00:39:32,184
But underneath, the tin cup
was rusted to the table.

435
00:39:32,225 --> 00:39:35,626
And then something caught
my father's eye.

436
00:39:35,662 --> 00:39:42,158
It was a gold doubloon
minted in Spain, 1867.

437
00:39:42,202 --> 00:39:44,864
My dad picked up the coin,
put it in his breast pocket...

438
00:39:44,904 --> 00:39:47,202
of his jacket,
and zippered it up.

439
00:39:47,240 --> 00:39:51,040
He came home,
told us the story.

440
00:39:51,077 --> 00:39:55,673
And he unzippered the pocket
to give me the coin.

441
00:39:55,715 --> 00:39:57,239
It was gone.

442
00:39:59,586 --> 00:40:01,577
I think I'll go
to Vancouver now.

443
00:40:07,927 --> 00:40:11,693
''April 21st. The deed is done.

444
00:40:11,731 --> 00:40:14,393
''Blake followed
our false fire on shore...

445
00:40:14,434 --> 00:40:18,234
''and his ship broke apart
on the rocks off Spivey Point.

446
00:40:18,271 --> 00:40:20,831
''We were aided
by an unearthly fog...

447
00:40:20,874 --> 00:40:23,570
''that rolled in
as if heaven-sent...

448
00:40:23,610 --> 00:40:27,410
''although God had no part
in our actions tonight.

449
00:40:27,447 --> 00:40:29,745
''Blake's gold
will be recovered tomorrow...

450
00:40:29,783 --> 00:40:34,345
''but may the Lord forgive us
for what we have done.''

451
00:40:34,387 --> 00:40:37,288
I couldn't read any further.

452
00:40:38,625 --> 00:40:42,493
Your grandfather
had a way with words.

453
00:40:44,664 --> 00:40:48,259
Our celebration tonight
is a travesty.

454
00:40:48,301 --> 00:40:50,963
We're honoring murderers.

455
00:41:41,121 --> 00:41:44,579
Side one,
KAB promos and lead-ins.

456
00:41:44,624 --> 00:41:49,493
More music on
top of the world KAB 1340.

457
00:41:50,930 --> 00:41:53,228
Thirty-three.

